<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n50082c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n50" href="#n50082c">N50 (VI.B.37)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n50all.htm#n50082c"> 82(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Ravengod</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Regardless of their former contests in the north itself, the Vikings were now united on these foreign shores by the ties of mutual interest and a common religion; and nothing, therefore, was more natural than that the ensign which conducted them in battle should be consecrated to Odin, or, as he was called, the father of victory, in whose presence they expected at some time to assemble and enjoy the delights of Valhalla. The eagle had been consecrated to Jupiter by the Romans; among the Northmen the raven was Odin&apos;s (or, the Father-of-all&apos;s) sacred bird. One of Odin&apos;s names was therefore <mark>&ldquo;Ravnegud&rdquo; (raven-god)</mark>. <small> J.J.A. Worsaae, <a name="JJAW2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JJAW2"><cite title="source">An Account of the Danes and Norwegians in England, Scotland and Ireland</cite></a> (1852) 56</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
